&lt;h2 id="introduction"&gt;Introduction
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;The area around Batworthy, covering both Shovel Down and Chagford Common, is unusually rich in ancient history, even for Dartmoor. Even though this walk is relatively short, and has only gentle inclines, we&amp;rsquo;ll encounter a lot of bronze age remains, starting with one of the best and largest hut circles on the moor. There&amp;rsquo;s also two tors included, one of which has some very well formed rock basins.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Road access is quite narrow and so we include some driving directions at the end, although a Satnav will generally find the way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="routing-box"&gt;
&lt;div class="routing-header"&gt;
&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/icons/signpost.svg"
alt=""
class="routing-icon"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="routing-content"&gt;
&lt;em&gt;When you&amp;rsquo;re ready to leave, walk back along the approach road for 350m until you encounter the large hutcircle on the left&lt;/em&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h2 id="round-pound"&gt;Round Pound
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1.jpg"
width="1909"
height="750"
srcset="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1_hu_4c8b383627060c6d.jpg 480w, https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/1_hu_fe3e686a4c7973f7.jpg 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Round Pound"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="254"
data-flex-basis="610px"
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Round Pound enclosure and hut circles at SX 6638 8684.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The outer stone walls, which are up to 4 metres wide and 2 metres high, are made from unusually large rocks and were used to enclose cattle at night to protect them from predators.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Inside the circle, which occupies 0.7 hectares, was a large central hut and another smaller hut. There are also several lower walls radiating out to form separate enclosures within the pound which were likely added during a much later medieval occupation&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s thought to have been first built in the early Iron Age, around 400 BC and iron smelting equipment was discovered during an archaeological dig in the 1950s. A Bronze Age arrowhead has also been found at this location, and much of the surrounding remains date from that earlier period.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class="link" href="https://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=MDV6117&amp;amp;resourceID=104" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;HER Devon &amp;amp; Dartmoor NDV6117 - Round Pound on Kes Tor, Gidleigh&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
