&lt;h2 id="long-stone-menhir"&gt;Long Stone Menhir
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;This impressive menhir is known as &amp;ldquo;Longstone&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;Long Stone&amp;rdquo; and stands three meters high. It&amp;rsquo;s linked to several nearby stone rows to the North. There is another smaller menhir a short way sound named Three Boys, but this has fallen. It&amp;rsquo;s so named as original there were three such menhirs but its brothers are believed to have &amp;ldquo;been taken for use as gateposts&amp;rdquo;. Like most of the remains of this walk, this is dated from the Bronze Age, around three to four thousand years ago. The boundary stone carvings imposed upon it are much more recent.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://dartmoorwalking.org/p/batworthy-and-chagford-common/22.jpg"
